It's true, if you remove guns from law abiding citizens, then the only people that have guns will be outlaws (I know that's not how the phrase goes, but you get the point).  This is simply a necessary evil at this point IMO.  We've dug ourselves into a hole by sprinkling guns everywhere, and now we may have to get a little dirty in order to get out.  Hypothetically, if we stopped the manufacturing of firearms it is likely that crime would go up, as criminals suddenly feel...liberated.  However over time those guns would break down, malfunction, get confiscated, run out of ammo(I'm assuming no one would manufacture ammunition once the guns were &quot;gone&quot;).  This would eventually lead to a &quot;gun free&quot; country.  Idealistic I know, but do-able.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Aside from that, It's quite obvious that guns are dangerous, but think about how many people's lives are saved everyday by guns in the hands of skilled and *legal* users.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Not many.  Statistically, the gun someone owns is more likely to be used on them or someone in their family, etc. Not some intruder.  So while I don't have an actual &quot;stat&quot; that I can reference off the top of my head, I've heard it many many times (or something similar) and I have NEVER heard it challenged (ie. it's actually used more on intruders than innocents).  It's a false sense of security that is more likely to harm you than help you.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And even if guns had never been developed, children and everyone else would still die accidentally by other means.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
True.  However every little bit helps.  Every year hundreds of people are killed/maimed by old land mines.  Does that mean I should go out and bury some more? No.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Also, if there were no guns... consider how brutal war would be... and don't say we wouldn't have war, because that simply isn't true. War is simply part of man's nature, it has been long before guns ever came along.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
War is war is war is war.  But the point of most gun control debates is to determine weather or not the average <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>citizen</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> should be allowed to possess firearms.  The military has nothing to do with it.  And if you want to argue the point that it would protect us against a possible tyranical government: a.) your desert eagle isn't going to do a damn thing against smart bombs, and b.) the military is made up of average people with average families (as opposed to some upper caste as was true in earlier cultures), so unless everyone in the military decides they want to gun down their own families it's not going to happen.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Ugh, this is retarded...if you don't think it's necessary, don't buy the @#%$ gun &amp; cartridge, and subsequently, shut the @#%$ up. All guns will possibly be used to kill people, it's an inherent risk that all gun manufacturers and owners have realized by now, so this tiresome charade isn't accomplishing anything in its billionth run on planet earth. You should be worried more about the more cheaper and mass manufactured weapons, because if you should be afraid of being gunned down by anything, it's not going to be a hand cannon that costed the owner around a thousand dollars to buy. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
